Movie Genre Popularity and Economic Activity¶

Akhilesh Mukadam¶

Introduction¶

Consumer sentiment plays an important role in driving economic activity. The effects of economic activity are reflected in the stock market. Positive consumer sentiment leads to high spending that leads to the appreciation of a company's share price. Inversely, negative consumer sentiment leads to less spending and depreciating share price.

One way of measuring consumer sentiment may be in the media they consume. Specifically with movies, the popularity of genres being produced and watched by consumers may reflect general consumer sentiment. After all, people do seek out specific genres, such as comedy, romance, or action, based on their moods.

Thee popularity of a genre may act as a contrarian indicator of consumer sentiment and negatively correlate with economic activity and stock performance. Alternatively, the popularity of a genre might reflect the attitude of customers at that time and positive correlate with economic activity and stock performance. A strong correlation, either negative or positive, may indicate a predictive or reactive relationship between genre popularity and economic activity. Such information could be valuable in making investment decisions or diagnosing economic health.

Data Collection and Data Tidying¶

First, I'll read in the relevant datasets and preprocess them in order to match our expository objectives.

Financial Data¶

In order to measure general economic activity, I'll utilize the S&P 500 Index. The S&P 500 is an index of the 500 largest publicly traded companies in the United States weighted by market capitalization, the size of company in dollars. Some of the companies in the S&P 500 are younger, such as Alphabet (Google), Amazon, and Facebook, while others are older, such as Disney, General Electric, and Ford. When the share prices of companies in the index depreciate, so does the index as a whole. Likewise, when the share price of companies appreciate, so does the index.

Read More: About the S&P 500

The S&P 500 data is available on Yahoo Finance in .csv format. The dataset contains daily-resolution index data from 1920 onwards. In order to make the dataset most relevant to our analysis, I have limited the data to the past 50 years, from 1970 onwards. Furthermore, I transformed the 'Date' column to a datetime format in order to improve functionality later.

In [3]:

For my analysis, I utilize 'Adj Close'. 'Adj Close' is the adjusted value of the index at 4:00 PM, the end of the trading day. The adjusted close accounts for corporate actions that affect the raw share price but not the share value. Events such as these (stock splits, dividends, etc.) are beyond the scope of this analysis.

As you can see, in the past ~50 years, the S&P 500 has appreciated more than 41,000%! If you invested \$10,000 into the index in 1970, today you would have approximately \\$410,000!

Movie Data¶

The data I used for movies is available on IMBD. The dataset includes entries for non-movie media such as TV shows, short films, and other misc. video. Thus, I preprocess the data in several ways. First, I remove all entries where the runtime, the genre, or the start year is unknown. Next, I transform the start year and runtime columns to from text to numeric. Then, I filter the dataset down to just movies with a runtime of 1 hour or greater. Lastly, I limit movies to titles in the 1970 to 2020 range to match the finanicial data.

In [7]:

A problem mentioned previously is that, in general, more movies were produced after 2000. Furthermore, some genres are far more popular than others e.g. Drama vs Mystery. For my analysis, I want to look at the relative popularity of a particular genre in excess to other genres in that year. This requires normalizing the data. I utilize Min-Max normalization.

Read More: Min-Max Normalization and other normalization techniques

In [12]:
def get_normalized_df(df):
    count_df = df.groupby("startYear").count()
    count_df = count_df[["tconst"]]
    return (count_df - count_df.mean())/(count_df.max() - count_df.min()) # min max normalization
 
# normalize movies
comedy_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(comedy_df)
horror_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(horror_df)
romance_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(romance_df)
action_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(action_df)
thriller_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(thriller_df)
drama_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(drama_df)
mystery_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(mystery_df)
movie_count_norm_df = get_normalized_df(movies_df)

Interestingly, we see a spike in Action movies from the mid 80s to the mid 90s. Most likely, this is studios trying to capitalize on the success of other well recieved action movie franchises, such as The Terminator (1984), Predator (1987), and Die Hard (1988), among others. There's also a similar spike for Romance movies from the mid 90s to the mid 2000s. Similarly, theres an early drop off in the Romance genre, although the reason for this is unknown.

Read More: NYT on American Action Movies

Relative Genre Popularity¶

Normalizing is helpful, but in order to determine if a certain genre predicts or reacts to consumer sentiment, I need to determine how popular it is relative to other genres at the time. The best way to do this is to take the normalized genre values and subtract the normalized values of all movies to calculate the genre's excess popularity for that year.

In [14]:
# comedies excess of normal movies
def get_genre_excess_df(count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df):
    excess_df = count_norm_df.copy()
    excess_df["excess"] = excess_df["tconst"] - movie_count_norm_df["tconst"] # get excess 
    excess_df = excess_df[["excess"]] # remove all other columns
    
    return excess_df

# get genre excess popularity
comedy_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(comedy_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)
horror_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(horror_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)
romance_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(romance_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)
action_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(action_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)
thriller_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(thriller_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)
drama_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(drama_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)
mystery_excess_df = get_genre_excess_df(mystery_count_norm_df, movie_count_norm_df)

Below is a plot of a genre's popularity excess for that year.

The above visualization really illustrates the meteoric rise in popularity of the Action genre from the mid 80s to the mid 90s in comparison to the previous visualization. It also shows a similar phenomenon for the Romance genre from the mid 90s to the mid 2000s. What is more apparent now is that following the rise of these genres is a proportionate fall in popularity. Perhaps audiences and studios exhuast a genre by repetition, leading to its subsequent decline in popularity. The exact reason this occurs is outside the scope of this analysis.

Normalizing the Financial Data¶

In order to make the movie data and financial data comparable, I must also normalize the S&P 500 data. First, I'll calculate the annual return. Then, I'll normalize those returns.

In [16]:
# get annual returns basedon daily returns
def get_annual_returns_df(df):
    df["Daily Return"] = df.groupby(df.Date.dt.year)["Adj Close"].apply(pd.Series.pct_change)
    return_df = df.groupby(df.Date.dt.year)["Daily Return"].sum().mul(100).reset_index().rename(columns = {"Daily Return": "Annual Return"})
    return_df = return_df.set_index("Date")
    return return_df

# normalize, min max
def get_normalized_returns_df(df):
    return (df - df.mean())/(df.max() - df.min())

sp500_return_df = get_annual_returns_df(sp500_df)
sp500_return_norm_df = get_normalized_returns_df(sp500_return_df)

Below is a plot of normalized S&P 500 returns, alongside the genre popularity excess:

Correlating Returns with Popularity Excess¶

With the normalized S&P 500 returns and the genre popularity excess, I can determine if the popularity of a genre correlates with economic activity.

In [18]:
def get_corr(returns_norm_df, excess_df):
    return returns_norm_df["Annual Return"].corr(excess_df["excess"])

# SP 500
spy_corr_df = pd.DataFrame(data = {
    "Genre": ["Comedy", "Horror", "Romance", "Action", "Thriller", "Drama", "Mystery"],
    "Correlation": [
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, comedy_excess_df),
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, horror_excess_df),
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, romance_excess_df),
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, action_excess_df),
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, thriller_excess_df),
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, drama_excess_df),
        get_corr(sp500_return_norm_df, mystery_excess_df)
    ]
})
spy_corr_df = spy_corr_df.set_index("Genre")
spy_corr_df

The magnitude of correlation is not substantial enough to make predictive or diagnostic decisions on.

However, while the popularity of a particular genre may not correlate well with a general market index such as the S&P 500, perhaps it correlates well with the stock prices of individual companys. Particularly, movie related companies may have a more noticable correlation with genre popularity.

Regression to Predict AMC's Returns¶

With a correlation of 0.705 and 0.574, lets see if we can predict AMC's returns for 2020 based on the popularity of the Romance and Thriller genres.

Below, I take the normalized count of Romance/Thriller movies, and fit it to the actual Adj. Close of AMC stock from 2013 to 2020. Then, I utilize the normalized count to determine predicted stock price for the same duration.

Conclusion¶

The initial investigation into whether a genre's popularity correlates with economic activity resulted in unsubstantial correlations that were not useful for predictive or diagnostic purposes. However, when looking at specific companies instead of the general market, there was an interesting correlation between the Romance and Thriller genre's popularity and AMC's stock returns.

A correlation of 0.705 and 0.574 respectively for the Romance and Thriller genres is substantial enough to warrant predictive analysis. Using the normalized count for Romance and Thriller movies, I fitted a Linear Regression model to the actual share price. Then, I used the normalized counts to predict the Stock price. The predictions were surprisingly accurate.

In conclusion, the popularity of certain genres does have a predictive impact on the price of certain stocks. In this case, the Romance and Thriller genres showed predictive capability.
